ctText>&lt;p>Driven largely by political concerns the asylum&amp;nbsp;and immigration system in Britain has been the subject of extensive legislative and policy reform since 1997, yet there is little reliable information about how the system actually functions nor how it affects asylum applicants. The asylum system clearly awards certain ?rights? (of residence, protection and future citizenship) to acknowledged ?refugees?, but it also disciplines and excludes far larger numbers of asylum applicants and ?illegal? immigrants. The system is regulated by national and international law; the former, implemented by the Home Office, tends towards a restrictive approach to asylum while the latter provides judges with a broader set of legal instrument with which to assess asylum cases.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>This project seeks to shed light on the tensions in and work of the asylum system by focusing on the experience of asylum applicants from the Horn of Africa (Ethiopia &amp;amp; Eritrea) through: &lt;/p> 
&lt;ol> 
 &lt;li>undertaking research with refugee communities in the UK about the situation experienced by individual asylum applicants;&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>researching the work of immigration lawyers/case-workers who prepare and argue individual asylum cases; and&lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>by analysing the work of the immigration (and, where necessary, the Administrative) Courts as they determine asylum claims.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>312622</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A91869AC-FDDA-429F-B496-700DF81F5618</gtr:id><gtr:title>Nationalism, Law and Statelessness: Grand Illusions in the Horn of Africa</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/66e7cd9d6f00a9a1263559cb624ee591"><gtr:id>66e7cd9d6f00a9a1263559cb624ee591</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Campbell John R.</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780415634939</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>i_70513198023b807f06</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>5702650F-39BE-4B38-814B-C3822D176A77</gtr:id><gtr:title>Language analysis in the United Kingdom's refugee status determination system: seeing through policy claims about 'expert knowledge'</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Ethnic and Racial Studies</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/ecc5e993c674c00c1809f57cc3439b36"><gtr:id>ecc5e993c674c00c1809f57cc3439b36</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Campbell J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cf98f98f7bd234</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A1A05B0B-F